Local LLM Runtime Observability System — Build Requirements

Objective
Provide a unified observability system for a local LLM experimentation environment that allows real-time monitoring and analysis of inference performance across multiple backends (vLLM, ExLlamaV2, Transformers/PyTorch, GGUF runtimes, and future engines). The system must operate alongside an existing TUI-driven runner and expose standardized runtime metrics that enable model loading verification, performance tuning, and backend comparison.

Scope
The system introduces a metrics instrumentation layer within the model runner and an external visualization stack. The runner remains the control interface for experiments while the observability system provides passive monitoring and historical analysis.

The system must support both production-grade inference engines (vLLM, ExLlamaV2) and experimental backends (raw Transformers/PyTorch) without requiring engine-specific dashboards.

Primary Deliverables

Metrics Instrumentation Layer (Runner Integration)
A standardized instrumentation layer embedded within the runner process that exposes runtime metrics describing model configuration, GPU usage, inference throughput, latency, batching behavior, and KV-cache utilization.

This layer must provide a unified metrics interface across all backends and expose metrics via a Prometheus-compatible HTTP endpoint.

Functional deliverables:

• metrics interface abstraction used by all engines
• backend adapters for each inference engine
• runtime metric collectors
• metrics HTTP endpoint
• metric lifecycle management during engine load/unload
• experiment metadata tagging

Supported backends:

• vLLM
• ExLlamaV2
• HuggingFace Transformers / PyTorch
• GGUF runtimes (llama.cpp based)
• future custom engines

Metrics must remain backend-agnostic and use the same schema regardless of runtime implementation.

Metrics Schema Definition
A standardized schema describing all metrics produced by the system. This schema ensures consistent visualization and enables cross-engine comparisons.

The schema must define the following metric categories.

Model Configuration Metrics

Purpose: verify how a model actually loaded into memory.

Required fields:

• model_identifier
• model_parameter_count
• model_weight_bytes
• model_dtype
• kv_cache_dtype
• quantization_type
• context_length
• engine_name
• engine_version

These metrics confirm whether the runtime configuration matches expected parameters.

GPU Metrics

Purpose: monitor hardware resource utilization.

Required fields:

• gpu_vram_total_bytes
• gpu_vram_used_bytes
• gpu_vram_reserved_bytes
• gpu_vram_free_bytes
• gpu_utilization_percent
• gpu_memory_bandwidth_percent
• gpu_power_usage_watts

These metrics may be sourced from GPU exporters or internal collectors.

PyTorch Runtime Metrics

Purpose: detect memory allocation behavior and tensor usage within raw transformer backends.

Required fields:

• torch_cuda_memory_allocated_bytes
• torch_cuda_memory_reserved_bytes
• torch_cuda_max_allocated_bytes
• torch_cuda_active_tensors

These metrics help detect silent dtype promotion, memory fragmentation, or allocator behavior.

KV Cache Metrics

Purpose: monitor attention memory allocation and runtime usage.

Required fields:

• kv_cache_total_bytes
• kv_cache_used_bytes
• kv_cache_utilization_ratio
• kv_cache_block_size
• kv_cache_sequence_count

These metrics are critical for tuning context length and batching parameters.

Throughput Metrics

Purpose: measure inference performance.

Required fields:

• tokens_generated_total
• tokens_generated_per_second
• effective_tokens_per_second
• requests_completed_total
• requests_in_flight
• requests_queued

Effective tokens/sec represents user-perceived performance including latency overhead.

Latency Metrics

Purpose: detect architectural bottlenecks.

Required fields:

• request_latency_seconds
• prefill_latency_seconds
• decode_latency_seconds
• time_to_first_token_seconds

Latency distributions must support percentile aggregation:

• p50
• p95
• p99

Batch Metrics

Purpose: analyze batching efficiency and request aggregation.

Required fields:

• batch_size_current
• batch_size_average
• batch_tokens_current
• batch_tokens_average

Generation Metrics

Purpose: monitor generation behavior and request characteristics.

Required fields:

• generation_tokens_requested
• generation_tokens_output
• generation_stop_reason
• generation_streaming_enabled

Experiment Metadata Metrics

Purpose: tag and differentiate experimental runs.

Required fields:

• experiment_id
• engine_name
• quantization_type
• kv_cache_quantization
• attention_backend
• model_variant

These tags allow comparison between runs.

Metrics Endpoint
The runner must expose a Prometheus-compatible metrics endpoint accessible via HTTP.

Deliverables:

• standardized /metrics endpoint
• structured metric export
• scrape compatibility with external collectors
• configurable update interval

This endpoint serves as the sole data source for external monitoring systems.

Observability Infrastructure
A monitoring stack responsible for collecting, storing, and visualizing runtime metrics.

Components required:

• Prometheus metrics collector
• Grafana visualization dashboard
• GPU metrics exporter
• system metrics exporter

The infrastructure must operate locally without cloud dependencies and support persistent metric storage for experiment comparison.

Visualization Dashboard
A set of Grafana dashboards designed specifically for local inference tuning.

Required dashboard panels.

Hardware Panel

Displays:

• GPU utilization
• VRAM usage
• memory bandwidth
• power consumption

Model Panel

Displays:

• model size
• dtype
• quantization configuration
• KV cache allocation

Throughput Panel

Displays:

• tokens/sec
• effective tokens/sec
• requests/sec
• batch size

Latency Panel

Displays:

• time to first token
• prefill latency
• decode latency
• request latency percentiles

Cache Panel

Displays:

• KV cache usage
• active sequences
• context utilization

Batch Panel

Displays:

• real-time batch size
• batch token count
• batching efficiency

These panels provide the live feedback loop required for runtime tuning.

Backend Metrics Adapters
Each engine must include a metrics adapter that maps engine-specific information into the standardized schema.

Adapters required for:

• vLLM runtime metrics
• ExLlamaV2 inference statistics
• HuggingFace / PyTorch profiling metrics
• GGUF runtime telemetry

The adapter layer ensures dashboards remain consistent regardless of backend.

Experiment Tracking Capability
The system must support labeling and comparing experiments.

Capabilities required:

• experiment identifiers
• configuration tagging
• metric comparison across runs
• time-series analysis of tuning changes

This allows users to observe the effect of configuration changes such as context size, quantization format, or batching limits.

Integration With Existing Runner
The observability system must operate alongside the existing TUI-based model runner.

Integration requirements:

• TUI remains the control interface
• dashboards operate as passive observers
• metrics update in real time during experiments
• no disruption to existing runner workflows

The runner must remain responsible for:

• model loading
• experiment execution
• backend selection

The observability system remains read-only.

System Outcome
Completion of this system provides a unified runtime observability environment enabling:

• verification of model loading behavior
• monitoring of GPU and memory usage
• measurement of inference performance
• comparison of backend implementations
• tuning of runtime parameters
• identification of inference bottlenecks

The system converts the local model runner into a full experimentation laboratory for LLM runtime optimization.